19 Revival of National Feeling. - One important result of this policy was a revival of national feeling and a deeper consciousness of the true greatness of Rome. Thepatriotic mind dwelt with pride on the thought that never before had the Roman domain been so extensive or so 'well governed, never before had the city been so beautiful and so well fitted to impress the imagination. The very establishment of the Empire, by embodying visibly in a single person the majesty and greatness of the state, made men realize more fully that majesty and greatness. Pride of empire was far stronger in the poets of the Augustan age than it had· been in their prede- cessors.
